    </tools>
    <applies-to>both</applies-to>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>IndieHackers Build-in-Public Strategy</title>

    <summary>A give-first community strategy for IndieHackers: spend 2–4 weeks helping others before any self-promotion, then build an audience through transparent build-in-public updates (monthly revenue reports, wins, losses). Community converts to customers only after you are recognized as a genuine contributor — not a promoter.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>IndieHackers is populated by solopreneurs who are also potential customers and referrers. Direct promotion without participation is rejected immediately. The mechanism: consistent helpful engagement builds reputation and followership; milestone posts (first sale, $1K MRR) generate high organic visibility and convert the community into word-of-mouth.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Building a product for other solopreneurs, indie hackers, or bootstrappers.</item>
        <item>Need early adopters and peer feedback from an experienced builder community.</item>
        <item>Product has a build-in-public story to tell (transparent revenue milestones).</item>
        <item>Looking for accountability partners, collaborators, or co-marketing.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>B2B enterprise or corporate-audience products — wrong community.</item>
        <item>Need customers immediately — IH requires 4–8 weeks before any promotion yields results.</item>
        <item>Product has nothing to do with building/running a business.</item>
        <item>Unwilling to share revenue numbers — transparency is the community norm; obscuring metrics reads as inauthentic.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="profile-setup">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Set up a complete profile before your first post: real photo, bio that states what you're building and your background, product page with revenue (even $0), and linked Twitter/X. Incomplete profiles are ignored.</statement>
        <rationale>IH community skims profiles before engaging. An incomplete profile signals low commitment. Transparent revenue — even zero — builds credibility because it shows honesty about current stage.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="give-first-period">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Spend 2–4 weeks answering questions, commenting on others' updates, and upvoting good content before making any post that mentions your product.</statement>
        <rationale>IH community detects newcomers who appear only to promote. Early-stage promotion without participation gets ignored or flagged. Reputation is a prerequisite for reach on the platform.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Answer "how do I..." questions in your domain — daily, 2–3 per day.</item>
        <item>Comment thoughtfully on other makers' updates — not just "congrats", but specific engagement with their challenge.</item>
        <item>Share relevant tools or resources that are not your own.</item>
        <item>Connect people in the community who should know each other.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="feedback-requests">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>When asking for feedback, specify exactly what you want feedback on, share context (what you've tried, what stage you're at), and include a screenshot or link. Reply to every comment.</statement>
        <rationale>Generic "feedback please" posts are skimmed over. Specific questions get specific answers. Replying to every comment signals engagement and generates ongoing discussion that boosts post visibility.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Asking "What do you think of my idea?" without context, stage information, or what kind of feedback you need.</description>
        <reason>Non-specific asks produce non-specific answers ("looks good!") that are useless. They also signal that the maker hasn't thought deeply about the problem.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="monthly-updates">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Post a monthly update covering: MRR and user count, what worked this month, what failed, key learnings, and one question for the community. Share both wins and losses — losses generate more engagement than wins.</statement>
        <rationale>Transparent vulnerability (sharing failures) builds stronger community bonds than success posts alone. IH readers are founders who face the same failures; they engage deeply with honest loss analysis. Wins without losses look like marketing.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>The monthly update structure should follow this template:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Headline with clear metrics (MRR, user count, churn rate)</item>
        <item>What worked this month — 2-3 bullet points with brief explanations</item>
        <item>What failed or didn't work — 1-2 items showing honest struggle</item>
        <item>Key learning from the month — one concrete insight</item>
        <item>Next month focus — what you're prioritizing</item>
        <item>Specific question for the community — not generic, but directly relevant to your challenge</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="milestone-posts">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Post milestone updates at: first sale, $100 MRR, $1K MRR, $10K MRR, first 100 users, first profitable month, and job quit day. Format: journey → what worked → what to do differently → open AMA.</statement>
        <rationale>These specific milestones are culturally significant to the IH community. They generate high engagement because readers are either approaching these milestones (aspirational) or have passed them (they can contribute experience). The AMA format creates ongoing discussion that keeps the post visible for days.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Milestone posts should include:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Journey narrative (100 words) — how you got here, key turning points</item>
        <item>What worked section (3 bullets with explanations) — tactics that moved the needle</item>
        <item>What I'd do differently (2 bullets) — honest reflection on mistakes and learnings</item>
        <item>Open "Ask me anything!" section — invites community to ask follow-up questions</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="posting-cadence">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Post minimum weekly (even brief updates) to maintain visibility in the feed. Disappearing for 3+ weeks resets community familiarity.</statement>
        <rationale>IH shows recent activity in maker profiles. Gaps signal stalled projects. Community builds relationships with consistent voices; irregular posters are forgotten between posts.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Only posting wins and growth numbers, hiding failures and pivots.</description>
        <reason>Reads as a marketing account, not a real maker. Community disengages. The most-shared IH posts are about failure, pivots, and hard lessons — not clean success stories.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Posting an update and not replying to comments for 2+ days.</description>
        <reason>Comment threads that the author ignores die immediately. Replies create ongoing discussion that keeps the post visible in the feed and signals you value the community's input.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="successful-example">
      <example type="good" title="Successful 12-Month IH Journey: Email Tool Developer">
        <description>Developer building an email productivity tool with 12 months of consistent participation and build-in-public.</description>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Approach:
  - Posted helpful answers daily for 1 month before product mention
  - Monthly transparent updates (revenue, wins, failures)
  - Asked specific feedback questions with screenshots
  - Celebrated milestones publicly with learnings
  - Applied for IH podcast after hitting $10K MRR

Results after 12 months:
  IH followers: 2,000
  Signups from IH: 500
  Paying customers from IH: 50
  IH podcast feature: 1 episode
  Community reputation: recognized domain expert
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Failed Approach: Promo-First Launch">
        <description>Maker with no prior participation submitted a promotional post on day one.</description>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Mistakes:
  - Posted "Check out my product" with no prior participation
  - No context, no story, no transparency
  - Didn't reply to the two critical comments received
  - Posted once and disappeared

Results:
  Upvotes: 5
  Comments: 2 (both critical)
  Signups from IH: 0
  Account activity afterward: zero
  Reputation: none (profile sits empty)
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-integration-and-limitations">
      <p>An agent is most useful for drafting the structured content (monthly updates, milestone posts, feedback request posts) from raw inputs the founder provides: this month's metrics, what worked, what failed, what they learned. The agent formats this into the IH post templates, writes in a first-person conversational style, and generates specific community questions to embed. The founder reviews and adjusts for authentic voice before posting. Agents can also help plan a 90-day content calendar: which milestones to post about, which feedback to seek, which questions to pose to the community.</p>

      <p>IndieHackers has no public API for posting or analytics; all content must be posted manually via the web interface. Community engagement is relationship-based; agent-generated content that lacks authentic voice will be recognized and receive poor engagement. IH audience is global and niche-diverse; product-market fit signal from IH validation is relevant mainly for other solopreneurs as an audience, not broader markets. Consistent posting requires 2-4 weeks of community participation before promotional content gains traction — agents cannot shortcut the reputation-building phase. Monthly update posts require real metrics; agents must be given accurate data, not asked to invent plausible numbers.</p>

      <p>Agent-drafted posts sound too polished and structured — IH community values genuine imperfection; instruct agent to use casual phrasing, contractions, and first-person narrative; then review and rough up the language. Monthly update posts require accurate current metrics; never ask the agent to estimate metrics — provide real numbers from Stripe/Plausible and let agent format them. Agents may generate community questions that are too generic ("What do you think?") — instruct agent to write questions that are specific to your product's current challenge. Human-in-loop checkpoint: all posts must be reviewed and personally adjusted by the founder before publishing — voice authenticity is the primary differentiator in build-in-public content. IH has no API; agents cannot check whether a post was received well, what comments came in, or whether to follow up — all community monitoring is manual. Cross-posting identical text to IH, Twitter/X, and LinkedIn without platform-specific adaptation performs poorly on each platform — agent should produce 3 separate versions from the same source material.</p>

      <p>Best practices: Share real numbers, including zero — "MRR: $0 (launched today)" earns more engagement than omitting metrics; IH culture rewards vulnerability. Frame failure posts as learnings, not complaints — "We tried X, it failed, here's why" gets 5-10x more comments than "X doesn't work for us". End every update post with a specific, answerable question — open-ended "any feedback?" gets ignored; "How do you handle pricing objections for a $49/month tool?" gets 20 replies. Cross-post monthly updates to Twitter/X as a thread within 24 hours of the IH post to maximize reach and IH follower growth. Apply for the IH podcast or interview at $10K MRR — it's the single highest-leverage IH content format, but only after achieving a real milestone. Comment on 2-3 other makers' posts before publishing your own each week; IH feed algorithms and community norms reward reciprocal engagement.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/intro-post.txt" purpose="First IH post: about me, product, current status, what I hope to get from the community."/>
      <template path="templates/monthly-update.txt" purpose="Monthly update: revenue, users, wins, losses, learnings, next month focus, community question."/>
      <template path="templates/milestone-post.txt" purpose="Milestone post: journey, what worked, what to do differently, AMA invite."/>
    </templates>

